===Verb===
{{en-verb|abdicat|ing}}

# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[disclaim]] and [[expel]] from the family, as a father his child; to [[disown]]; to [[disinherit]]. {{defdate|Mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{reference-book | last =| first = | authorlink =  | coauthors =  | editor =Brown, Lesley  | others =  | title = The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary | origdate =  | origyear = 1933| origmonth =  | url =  | format =  | accessdate =  | accessyear =  | accessmonth =  | edition = 5th | date =  | year =2003| month =  | publisher =Oxford University Press  | location =Oxford, UK | language =  | id =  | doi = | isbn =978-0-19-860575-7 | lccn = | ol = | pages =3| chapter =  | chapterurl =  | quote =}}</ref>
# {{transitive|obsolete}} To formally separate oneself from or to divest oneself of. {{defdate|Mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[depose]]. {{defdate|Early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[reject]]; to [[cast off]]; to discard. {{defdate|Mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{transitive}} To [[surrender]], [[renounce]] or [[relinquish]], as sovereign power; to [[withdraw]] [[definitely]] from filling or [[exercising]], as a high office, station, dignity; as, to ''abdicate'' the throne, the crown, the [[papacy]]. {{defdate|Mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''Note:'' The word ''abdicate'' was held to mean, in the case of James II, to abandon without a formal surrender.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]:
#*: The cross-bearers '''abdicated''' their service.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Edmund Burke|Edmund Burke]]:
#*: He '''abdicates''' all right to be his own governor.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:James Anthony Froude|James Anthony Froude]]:
#*: The understanding '''abdicates''' its functions.
# {{intransitive}} To relinquish or renounce a throne, or other high office or dignity; to renounce [[sovereignty]]. {{defdate|Early 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Edmund Burke|Edmund Burke]]:
#*: Though a king may '''abdicate''' for his own person, he cannot '''abdicate''' for the monarchy.

